1
00:00:03,712 --> 00:00:06,590
(WHOOSHING)

2
00:00:09,134 --> 00:00:12,304
Oh, smell that air.

3
00:00:12,387 --> 00:00:15,891
Grass and lemonade
and a little bit of mint.

4
00:00:16,016 --> 00:00:18,519
Just a hint of mint,
it must be the 1920's.

5
00:00:18,602 --> 00:00:21,772
You can tell what year it is,
just by smelling?

6
00:00:21,897 --> 00:00:22,981
Oh, yeah.

7
00:00:23,065 --> 00:00:27,027
Or maybe that big vintage car,
coming up the drive, gave it away.

8
00:00:30,531 --> 00:00:31,865
(HONKING)

9
00:00:34,493 --> 00:00:36,578
The professor's luggage,
Richard, step lively.

10
00:00:39,581 --> 00:00:42,543
-Good afternoon, Professor Peach.
-Hello, Greeves, old man.

11
00:00:42,626 --> 00:00:43,710
(CYCLE BELL RINGING)

12
00:00:43,794 --> 00:00:47,548
-Ah, Reverend.
-Professor Peach. Beautiful day.

13
00:00:47,631 --> 00:00:49,675
Lord's in his heaven,
all's right with the world.

14
00:00:49,800 --> 00:00:51,510
Reverend Golightly.

15
00:00:51,593 --> 00:00:55,264
Lady Eddison requests that you make
yourselves comfortable in your rooms.

16
00:00:55,347 --> 00:00:58,559
Cocktails will be served on the lawn
from half past four.

17
00:00:58,642 --> 00:01:01,144
You go on up. I need to check
something in the library.

18
00:01:01,228 --> 00:01:02,563
-Oh?
-Alone.

19
00:01:02,646 --> 00:01:07,025
It's supposed to be a party.
All this work'll be the death of you.

20
00:01:07,109 --> 00:01:12,447
Never mind planet Zog! A party
in the 1920's, that's more like it.

21
00:01:12,531 --> 00:01:15,284
Trouble is, we haven't been invited.

22
00:01:15,409 --> 00:01:17,995
Oh, I forgot. Yes, we have.

23
00:01:20,163 --> 00:01:21,999
(SOFTLY) I was right.

24
00:01:22,124 --> 00:01:26,587
Kept secret all these years.
It's unbelievable.

25
00:01:26,670 --> 00:01:28,213
But why didn't they ask... Heavens.

26
00:01:28,297 --> 00:01:29,631
(BUZZING)

27
00:01:29,715 --> 00:01:34,052
Oh, it's you.
I was just doing a little research.

28
00:01:34,177 --> 00:01:36,680
I say, what are you
doing with that lead piping?

29
00:01:36,763 --> 00:01:38,890
(BUZZING)

30
00:01:38,974 --> 00:01:40,475
That's impossible.

31
00:01:40,559 --> 00:01:42,019
No! No!

32
00:01:42,144 --> 00:01:43,979
(DOCTOR WHO THEME)

33
00:02:21,892 --> 00:02:24,227
We'll be late for cocktails.

34
00:02:27,022 --> 00:02:30,901
What do you think, flapper or slapper?

35
00:02:31,360 --> 00:02:33,445
Flapper. You look lovely.

36
00:02:43,288 --> 00:02:45,248
Look sharp. We have guests.

37
00:02:45,374 --> 00:02:49,252
-Good afternoon.
-Drinks, sir, ma'am?

38
00:02:49,378 --> 00:02:52,589
-A sidecar, please.
-And a lime soda. Thank you.

39
00:02:52,673 --> 00:02:55,384
May I announce Lady Clemency Eddison.

40
00:02:55,467 --> 00:02:57,427
Lady Eddison.

41
00:02:57,552 --> 00:03:00,972
Forgive me,
but who exactly might you be?

42
00:03:01,098 --> 00:03:03,684
-And what are you doing here?
-I'm the Doctor

43
00:03:03,809 --> 00:03:07,270
and this is Miss Donna Noble,
of the Chiswick Nobles.

44
00:03:07,354 --> 00:03:12,192
Good afternoon, my lady.
Topping day, what? Spiffing. Top hole.

45
00:03:12,275 --> 00:03:15,362
No, no, no, no, no.
No, don't do that. Don't.

46
00:03:15,445 --> 00:03:17,781
We were thrilled to receive
your invitation, milady.

47
00:03:17,906 --> 00:03:21,785
-We met at the Ambassador's reception.
-Doctor, how could I forget you?

48
00:03:21,868 --> 00:03:25,122
But one must be sure
with the Unicorn on the loose.

49
00:03:25,247 --> 00:03:27,374
A unicorn? Brilliant. Where?

50
00:03:27,457 --> 00:03:32,254
The Unicorn. A jewel thief
and nobody knows who he is.

51
00:03:32,337 --> 00:03:34,047
He's just struck again.

52
00:03:34,131 --> 00:03:37,843
Snatched Lady Babington's pearls
right from under her nose.

53
00:03:37,968 --> 00:03:39,886
-Funny place to wear pearls.
-May I announce

54
00:03:39,970 --> 00:03:43,974
the Colonel Hugh Curbishley,
the Honourable Roger Curbishley.

55
00:03:44,099 --> 00:03:47,519
(GIGGLING) My husband and my son.

56
00:03:47,644 --> 00:03:49,187
Forgive me for not rising.

57
00:03:49,312 --> 00:03:52,858
Never been the same ever since
that 'flu epidemic back in '18.

58
00:03:52,941 --> 00:03:56,236
My word. You are a super lady.

59
00:03:56,319 --> 00:03:59,865
Oh, I like the colour of your jib.
Chin-chin.

60
00:03:59,990 --> 00:04:01,742
-Hello, I'm the Doctor.
-How do you do?

61
00:04:01,825 --> 00:04:04,411
-Very well.
-Your usual, sir?

62
00:04:04,494 --> 00:04:06,955
Thank you, Davenport.
Just how I like it.

63
00:04:07,038 --> 00:04:10,500
How come she's an Eddison,
but her husband and son are Curbishleys?

64
00:04:10,584 --> 00:04:15,756
The Eddison title descends through her.
One day, Roger will be a Lord.

65
00:04:15,839 --> 00:04:17,257
Robina Redmond.

66
00:04:17,340 --> 00:04:21,428
She's the absolute hit
of the social scene, a must.

67
00:04:21,511 --> 00:04:25,682
-Miss Redmond.
-Spiffing to meet you at last, milady.

68
00:04:25,807 --> 00:04:31,730
-Reverend Arnold Golightly.
-Ah, Reverend. How are you?

69
00:04:31,813 --> 00:04:34,775
I heard about the church
last Thursday night.

70
00:04:34,858 --> 00:04:37,986
-Those ruffians breaking in.
-You apprehended them, I hear.

71
00:04:38,069 --> 00:04:42,157
As the Christian fathers taught me,
we must forgive them their trespasses,

72
00:04:42,240 --> 00:04:43,366
quite literally.

73
00:04:43,450 --> 00:04:46,203
Some of these young boys
deserve a decent thrashing.

74
00:04:46,286 --> 00:04:47,454
Couldn't agree more, sir.

75
00:04:47,537 --> 00:04:48,580
(CLEARS THROAT)

76
00:04:48,705 --> 00:04:51,792
(SOFTLY) Typical.
All the decent men are on the other bus.

77
00:04:51,875 --> 00:04:53,126
-Or Time Lords.
-REVEREND: Now, milady,

78
00:04:53,210 --> 00:04:55,420
what about the special guest
you promised us?

79
00:04:55,504 --> 00:05:00,926
Here she is.
A lady who needs no introduction.

80
00:05:01,051 --> 00:05:03,178
No, no, please don't.

81
00:05:03,261 --> 00:05:06,556
Thank you, Lady Eddison,
but, honestly, there is no need.

82
00:05:06,681 --> 00:05:09,351
-Agatha Christie.
-What about her?

83
00:05:09,434 --> 00:05:14,147
-That's me.
-No. You're kidding.

84
00:05:14,231 --> 00:05:16,983
Agatha Christie. I was just talking
about you the other day.

85
00:05:17,067 --> 00:05:19,277
I said, "I bet she's brilliant”.
I'm the Doctor, this is Donna.

86
00:05:19,361 --> 00:05:22,364
Oh! I love your stuff. What a mind.

87
00:05:22,447 --> 00:05:24,950
You fool me every time.
Well, almost every time.

88
00:05:25,033 --> 00:05:30,497
Well, once or twice. Well, once.
But it was a good once.

89
00:05:30,580 --> 00:05:32,249
You make a rather unusual couple.

90
00:05:32,332 --> 00:05:33,792
-Oh, no, we're not married.
-No, we're not a couple.

91
00:05:33,875 --> 00:05:36,586
Well, obviously not. No wedding ring.

92
00:05:37,587 --> 00:05:40,924
-Oh. You don't miss a trick.
-And I'd stay that way, if I were you.

93
00:05:41,007 --> 00:05:44,386
The thrill is in the chase,
never in the capture.

94
00:05:44,469 --> 00:05:47,305
Mrs Christie,
I'm so glad you could come.

95
00:05:47,430 --> 00:05:52,477
I'm one of your greatest followers.
I've read all six of your books.

96
00:05:52,561 --> 00:05:57,691
-Is Mr Christie not joining us?
-Is he needed?

97
00:05:57,774 --> 00:05:59,985
Can't a woman
make her own way in the world?

98
00:06:00,068 --> 00:06:01,653
Don't give my wife ideas.

99
00:06:01,736 --> 00:06:03,530
Now, Mrs Christie, I have a question.

100
00:06:03,613 --> 00:06:05,949
-Why a Belgian detective?
-Excuse me, Colonel.

101
00:06:06,074 --> 00:06:08,451
Belgians make such lovely buns.

102
00:06:08,577 --> 00:06:10,120
(LAUGHING)

103
00:06:12,163 --> 00:06:15,625
Say, where on Earth's Professor Peach?
He'd love to meet Mrs Christie.

104
00:06:15,709 --> 00:06:17,878
He said he was going to the library.

105
00:06:19,045 --> 00:06:22,257
Miss Chandrakala, would you go
and collect the Professor?

106
00:06:22,340 --> 00:06:26,678
-At once, milady.
-The date on this newspaper...

107
00:06:26,761 --> 00:06:28,513
What about it?

108
00:06:28,597 --> 00:06:31,975
It's the day
Agatha Christie disappeared.

109
00:06:35,645 --> 00:06:37,230
Professor Peach?

110
00:06:41,693 --> 00:06:42,777
Professor?

111
00:06:46,197 --> 00:06:49,910
She just discovered
her husband was having an affair.

112
00:06:49,993 --> 00:06:52,537
DONNA: You'd never think to look at her,
smiling away.

113
00:06:52,662 --> 00:06:57,709
Well. She's British, moneyed.
That's what they do. They carry on.

114
00:06:58,793 --> 00:07:00,670
Except for this one time.

115
00:07:00,837 --> 00:07:03,131
No one knows exactly what happened,
she just vanished.

116
00:07:08,178 --> 00:07:11,389
Her car will be found tomorrow morning,
by the side of a lake.

117
00:07:11,514 --> 00:07:15,060
Ten days later, Agatha Christie turns up
at a hotel in Harrogate.

118
00:07:17,187 --> 00:07:19,606
And she'd lost her memory.

119
00:07:19,689 --> 00:07:22,817
She never spoke about the disappearance
till the day she died.

120
00:07:22,901 --> 00:07:26,279
-But whatever it was...
-It's about to happen.

121
00:07:26,363 --> 00:07:28,531
Right here, right now.

122
00:07:28,615 --> 00:07:32,369
Professor! The library! Murder! Murder!

123
00:07:37,374 --> 00:07:39,417
(GASPS) Goodness.

124
00:07:39,501 --> 00:07:41,753
Bashed on the head. Blunt instrument.

125
00:07:42,754 --> 00:07:46,216
Watch broke as he fell.
Time of death was quarter past four.

126
00:07:46,299 --> 00:07:47,717
A bit of pipe.

127
00:07:48,426 --> 00:07:52,514
Call me Hercule Poirot,
but I reckon that's blunt enough.

128
00:07:56,601 --> 00:07:59,104
Nothing worth killing for in that lot.
Dry as dust.

129
00:08:00,522 --> 00:08:03,525
Doctor, the body in the library.

130
00:08:03,608 --> 00:08:07,779
I mean, Professor Peach, in the library,
with a lead piping.

131
00:08:07,862 --> 00:08:09,280
EDDISON: Let me see.
HUGH: Out of my way.

132
00:08:09,406 --> 00:08:10,490
Gerald.

133
00:08:10,949 --> 00:08:12,117
(ALL GASP)

134
00:08:12,200 --> 00:08:14,327
-Someone should call the police.
-DOCTOR: You don't have to.

135
00:08:14,411 --> 00:08:16,955
Chief Inspector Smith,
from Scotland Yard, known as the Doctor.

136
00:08:17,038 --> 00:08:19,207
Miss Noble is the plucky young girl
who helps me out.

137
00:08:19,290 --> 00:08:20,875
-I say.
-Mrs Christie was right.

138
00:08:20,959 --> 00:08:23,628
Go into the sitting room.
I will question each of you in turn.

139
00:08:23,712 --> 00:08:28,049
Come along, do as the Doctor says.
Keep the room undisturbed.

140
00:08:28,133 --> 00:08:30,176
"The plucky young girl
who helps me out?"

141
00:08:30,260 --> 00:08:32,470
No policewomen in 1926.

142
00:08:32,554 --> 00:08:35,306
I'll pluck you in a minute.
Why don't we phone the real police?

143
00:08:35,432 --> 00:08:38,768
Oh, the last thing we want
is PC Plod sticking his nose in.

144
00:08:38,852 --> 00:08:42,772
Especially, now I've found this.

145
00:08:43,898 --> 00:08:47,569
-Morphic residue.
-Morphic? Doesn't sound very 1926.

146
00:08:47,652 --> 00:08:51,740
It has left behind
a return species' genetic immune code.

147
00:08:51,823 --> 00:08:53,533
The murderer's an alien.

148
00:08:53,616 --> 00:08:55,869
Which means one of that lot
is a alien in human form.

149
00:08:55,952 --> 00:08:57,704
Yeah, but think about it.

150
00:08:57,787 --> 00:09:01,374
There's a murder,
a mystery and Agatha Christie.

151
00:09:01,458 --> 00:09:04,044
(SNIFFS) So? Happens to me all the time.

152
00:09:04,127 --> 00:09:06,838
No. But isn't that a bit weird?

153
00:09:06,963 --> 00:09:11,468
Agatha Christie didn't go around
surrounded by murders, not really.

154
00:09:11,551 --> 00:09:13,303
I mean, that's like
meeting Charles Dickens

155
00:09:13,428 --> 00:09:17,891
and he's surrounded by ghosts
at Christmas.

156
00:09:17,974 --> 00:09:19,517
-Well...
-Oh, come on.

157
00:09:19,601 --> 00:09:21,144
It's not like we could
drive across country

158
00:09:21,269 --> 00:09:24,230
and find Enid Blyton
having tea with Noddy.

159
00:09:24,314 --> 00:09:29,402
Could we? Noddy's not real. Is he?
Tell me there's no Noddy.

160
00:09:30,028 --> 00:09:31,654
There's no Noddy.

161
00:09:31,738 --> 00:09:32,947
Next thing you know,
you'll be telling me

162
00:09:33,031 --> 00:09:36,493
it's like Murder on the Orient Express,
and they all did it.

163
00:09:36,576 --> 00:09:40,538
-Murder on the Orient Express?
-Oh, yeah, one of the best.

164
00:09:40,622 --> 00:09:42,499
But not yet.

165
00:09:42,582 --> 00:09:44,751
-Marvellous idea, though.
-Yeah.

166
00:09:44,834 --> 00:09:48,171
Tell you what,
copyright, Donna Noble. Okay?

167
00:09:48,296 --> 00:09:51,257
Anyway, Agatha and I
will question the suspects.

168
00:09:51,341 --> 00:09:53,009
Donna, you search the bedrooms,
look for clues.

169
00:09:53,093 --> 00:09:56,179
(WHISPERING) Any more residues.
You'll need this.

170
00:09:56,262 --> 00:09:59,808
-Is that for real.
-Go on, you're ever so plucky.

171
00:10:01,726 --> 00:10:05,396
Right, then, solving a murder mystery
with Agatha Christie. Brilliant.

172
00:10:05,522 --> 00:10:08,525
How like a man to have fun
while there is disaster all around him.

173
00:10:08,650 --> 00:10:11,694
-Sorry, yeah.
-I'll work with you, gladly.

174
00:10:11,820 --> 00:10:15,365
But for the sake of justice,
not your own amusement.

175
00:10:20,495 --> 00:10:26,042
Now, then, Reverend,
where were you at a quarter past four?

176
00:10:26,126 --> 00:10:27,377
Let me think.

177
00:10:28,837 --> 00:10:30,755
Why, yes, I remember.

178
00:10:31,714 --> 00:10:34,300
I was unpacking in my room.

179
00:10:34,384 --> 00:10:37,428
DOCTOR: No alibi, then?
AGATHA: You were alone?

180
00:10:37,971 --> 00:10:41,182
With the Lord
one is never truly alone.

181
00:10:41,266 --> 00:10:43,101
-Doctor?
-And where were you?

182
00:10:43,226 --> 00:10:44,978
Let me think, I was...

183
00:10:45,061 --> 00:10:49,149
Oh, yes, I was taking a constitutional
in the fields behind the house.

184
00:10:51,943 --> 00:10:55,238
Just taking a stroll, that's all.

185
00:10:55,321 --> 00:10:58,408
-DOCTOR: Alone?
-Oh, yes. All alone, totally alone.

186
00:10:58,533 --> 00:11:01,786
Absolutely alone. Completely.
All of the time.

187
00:11:01,911 --> 00:11:04,747
I wandered lonely
as the proverbial cloud.

188
00:11:04,873 --> 00:11:09,502
There was no one else with me.
Not at all. Not ever.

189
00:11:09,586 --> 00:11:13,089
-And, where were you?
-At a quarter past four?

190
00:11:13,214 --> 00:11:16,634
Well, I went to the toilet
when I arrived, and then...

191
00:11:19,596 --> 00:11:23,808
Oh, yes, I remember.
I was preparing myself.

192
00:11:23,933 --> 00:11:25,935
Positively buzzing with excitement
about the party

193
00:11:26,060 --> 00:11:28,438
and the super fun of meeting Lady Eddie.

194
00:11:28,521 --> 00:11:30,523
DOCTOR: We've only got your word for it.

195
00:11:30,607 --> 00:11:33,359
That's your problem, not mine.

196
00:11:33,443 --> 00:11:35,111
And, where were you, sir?

197
00:11:35,236 --> 00:11:39,073
Quarter past four?
Dear me! Let me think.

198
00:11:39,157 --> 00:11:40,700
Ah, yes, I remember.

199
00:11:42,368 --> 00:11:46,998
I was in me study,
reading through some military memoirs.

200
00:11:47,081 --> 00:11:49,542
Fascinating stuff.

201
00:11:49,626 --> 00:11:55,173
Took me back to me days in the army.
Started reminiscing.

202
00:11:55,256 --> 00:11:59,010
Mafeking... Terrible war.

203
00:11:59,093 --> 00:12:00,803
DOCTOR: Colonel, snap out of it.

204
00:12:03,473 --> 00:12:06,351
-I was in me study.
-No, no, no, right out of it.

205
00:12:06,434 --> 00:12:11,022
Oh, sorry. Got a bit carried away there.

206
00:12:11,147 --> 00:12:14,901
And where were you
at a quarter past four, milady?

207
00:12:14,984 --> 00:12:17,028
Now, let me see.

208
00:12:18,529 --> 00:12:21,908
Yes, I remember.
I was sitting in the blue room,

209
00:12:21,991 --> 00:12:25,995
taking my afternoon tea.
It's a ritual of mine.

210
00:12:26,079 --> 00:12:30,333
I needed to gather strength
for the duty of hostess.

211
00:12:30,458 --> 00:12:34,879
I then proceeded to the lawn,
where I met you, Doctor,

212
00:12:34,963 --> 00:12:40,134
and I said, "And who exactly might
you be and what were you doing here?"

213
00:12:40,218 --> 00:12:45,139
And you said, "I am the Doctor
and this is Miss Donna Noble..."”

214
00:12:45,223 --> 00:12:48,393
Yes, yes, you can stop now.
I was there for that bit.

215
00:12:48,518 --> 00:12:49,644
Of course.

216
00:12:49,727 --> 00:12:53,022
(BURPS) Excuse me.

217
00:12:53,106 --> 00:12:54,899
No alibis for any of them.

218
00:12:56,150 --> 00:12:59,529
Secret adversary remains hidden.

219
00:13:01,155 --> 00:13:05,910
We must look for a motive.
Use the little, grey cells.

220
00:13:05,994 --> 00:13:10,456
Oh, yes. Little, grey cells.
Good ol' Poirot.

221
00:13:10,540 --> 00:13:14,377
You know, I've been to Belgium, yeah.

222
00:13:14,460 --> 00:13:15,670
I remember.

223
00:13:17,255 --> 00:13:21,217
I was deep in the Ardennes,
trying to find Charlemagne.

224
00:13:21,301 --> 00:13:23,928
He'd been kidnapped
by an insane computer.

225
00:13:24,012 --> 00:13:26,556
AGATHA: Doctor! Doctor!

226
00:13:26,639 --> 00:13:27,890
Sorry.

227
00:13:27,974 --> 00:13:32,145
-Charlemagne lived centuries ago.
-I've got a very good memory.

228
00:13:32,228 --> 00:13:34,897
For such an experience, Detective,
you missed a big clue.

229
00:13:35,023 --> 00:13:36,774
What, that bit of paper
you nicked out of the fire?

230
00:13:36,858 --> 00:13:38,109
-You were looking the other way.
-Yeah,

231
00:13:38,234 --> 00:13:41,571
but I saw you reflected
in the glass of the bookcase.

232
00:13:42,405 --> 00:13:44,866
You crafty man.

233
00:13:44,949 --> 00:13:47,910
This is all that was left.

234
00:13:50,830 --> 00:13:52,457
DOCTOR: What's that first letter,
I IN I I or IIMII?

235
00:13:52,540 --> 00:13:54,083
AGATHA: It's an "M".
The word is "maiden".

236
00:13:54,167 --> 00:13:56,502
Maiden! What does that mean?

237
00:13:56,586 --> 00:13:59,088
(SIGHS) We're still no further forward.

238
00:13:59,213 --> 00:14:03,843
Our nemesis remains at large.
Unless Miss Noble's found something.

239
00:14:13,436 --> 00:14:15,646
You won't find anything.

240
00:14:17,106 --> 00:14:20,485
-How come it's locked?
-Lady Eddison commands it to be so.

241
00:14:20,610 --> 00:14:25,114
And I command it to be otherwise.
Scotland Yard. Pip, pip.

242
00:14:28,785 --> 00:14:31,245
Why was it locked in the first place?

243
00:14:31,329 --> 00:14:34,957
Many years ago,
when my father was butler to the family,

244
00:14:35,083 --> 00:14:38,086
Lady Eddison returned
from India with malaria.

245
00:14:38,169 --> 00:14:41,464
She locked herself in this room
for six months until she recovered.

246
00:14:41,547 --> 00:14:45,968
Since then,
the room has remained undisturbed.

247
00:14:49,639 --> 00:14:52,642
There's nothing in here.

248
00:14:52,725 --> 00:14:56,687
-How long has it been empty?
-Forty years.

249
00:14:56,771 --> 00:14:59,607
Why did she seal it off?

250
00:15:00,691 --> 00:15:04,904
All right, I need to investigate.
You just buttle off.

251
00:15:20,586 --> 00:15:22,296
(INSECT BUZZING)

252
00:15:25,299 --> 00:15:27,510
1926, they've still got bees.

253
00:15:30,513 --> 00:15:34,892
Oh, what noise. All right, busy bee,
I'll let you out. Hold on.

254
00:15:35,977 --> 00:15:41,023
I shall find you
with my amazing powers of detection.

255
00:15:46,028 --> 00:15:47,405
(GASPS)

256
00:15:50,241 --> 00:15:52,243
(SCREAMING)

257
00:15:53,494 --> 00:15:55,204
It's impossible.

258
00:15:58,207 --> 00:15:59,417
Doctor!

259
00:16:02,837 --> 00:16:04,630
(SCREECHING)

260
00:16:06,215 --> 00:16:08,676
Doctor!

261
00:16:09,385 --> 00:16:11,012
(WOOD SHATTERING)

262
00:16:13,222 --> 00:16:16,267
There is a giant wasp.

263
00:16:16,392 --> 00:16:20,605
-What do you mean a giant wasp?
-I mean, a wasp that's giant.

264
00:16:20,688 --> 00:16:22,773
It's only a silly, little insect.

265
00:16:22,899 --> 00:16:25,735
When I say giant, I don't mean big.

266
00:16:25,860 --> 00:16:29,822
I mean flipping enormous!
Look at its sting.

267
00:16:31,407 --> 00:16:33,034
Let me see.

268
00:16:34,035 --> 00:16:36,412
It's gone. Buzzed off.

269
00:16:39,540 --> 00:16:41,334
But that's fascinating.

270
00:16:41,417 --> 00:16:45,713
Don't, don't...
Don't touch it, don't touch it. Let me.

271
00:16:45,796 --> 00:16:47,089
A giant wasp?

272
00:16:47,757 --> 00:16:51,093
Well, tons of amorphous,
insectivorous life forms,

273
00:16:51,177 --> 00:16:54,055
but none in this galactic vector.

274
00:16:54,138 --> 00:16:56,849
I think I understood
some of those words.

275
00:16:56,933 --> 00:16:59,143
Enough to know
that you're completely potty.

276
00:16:59,227 --> 00:17:01,270
Lost its sting.
Now, that makes it defenceless.

277
00:17:01,354 --> 00:17:03,898
A creature this size
got to be able to grow a new one.

278
00:17:03,981 --> 00:17:08,861
Uh, can we return to sanity?
There are no such things as giant wasps.

279
00:17:08,945 --> 00:17:13,491
Exactly, so...
Question is, what's it doing here?

280
00:17:16,202 --> 00:17:19,413
A murder? That's put the cat
among the pigeons and no mistake.

281
00:17:19,497 --> 00:17:23,417
It is not the stuff of gossip, Mrs Hart.
Continue with your work.

282
00:17:23,501 --> 00:17:25,753
But, who'd want to do in
the old Professor?

283
00:17:25,836 --> 00:17:28,172
He was always asking questions
about that book of his.

284
00:17:28,256 --> 00:17:32,134
-What was all that about?
-A dead man's folly, nothing more.

285
00:17:33,886 --> 00:17:36,430
Perhaps, if he asked about...

286
00:17:37,306 --> 00:17:39,475
I must go and see milady.

287
00:17:47,942 --> 00:17:49,652
(SCREAMING)

288
00:17:49,777 --> 00:17:51,153
(THUDDING)

289
00:18:00,246 --> 00:18:05,668
The poor, little child.

290
00:18:06,752 --> 00:18:08,963
(WASP BUZZING)

291
00:18:09,046 --> 00:18:10,339
There!

292
00:18:12,675 --> 00:18:14,260
Come on!

293
00:18:14,343 --> 00:18:17,888
This makes a change.
There's a monster and we're chasing it.

294
00:18:17,972 --> 00:18:21,267
Every monster has a trick.
They do it with mirrors.

295
00:18:26,981 --> 00:18:28,232
Oh, my God, that's holy.

296
00:18:28,357 --> 00:18:31,319
Oh. Well, you are wonderful.

297
00:18:34,363 --> 00:18:37,450
Now, just stop. Stop there.

298
00:18:37,992 --> 00:18:39,410
(ALL GASP)

299
00:18:41,370 --> 00:18:43,873
Oi, fly boy.

300
00:18:47,335 --> 00:18:51,297
DOCTOR: Don't let it get away! Quick,
before it reverts back to human form!

301
00:18:51,380 --> 00:18:55,801
Where are you? Come on.
There's nowhere to run. Show yourself.

302
00:18:59,305 --> 00:19:00,556
Oh.

303
00:19:02,725 --> 00:19:04,268
That's just cheating.

304
00:19:05,227 --> 00:19:08,272
My faithful companion. This is terrible.

305
00:19:08,397 --> 00:19:12,610
Excuse me, milady. She was on her way
to tell you something.

306
00:19:12,693 --> 00:19:14,445
She never found me.

307
00:19:14,528 --> 00:19:17,114
She had an appointment
with death instead.

308
00:19:17,239 --> 00:19:21,911
She said, "The poor, little child".
Does that mean anything to anyone?

309
00:19:22,036 --> 00:19:27,249
No children in this house for years.
Highly unlikely there will be any.

310
00:19:27,500 --> 00:19:28,751
(CLEARS THROAT)

311
00:19:28,834 --> 00:19:32,296
Mrs Christie, you must have
twigged something.

312
00:19:32,380 --> 00:19:35,174
You've written simply
the best detective stories.

313
00:19:35,257 --> 00:19:38,469
Tell us, what would Poirot do?

314
00:19:38,594 --> 00:19:42,932
Heaven's sake, cards on the table,
woman. You should be helping us.

315
00:19:43,015 --> 00:19:48,688
-But...I'm merely a writer.
-But surely you can crack it.

316
00:19:48,771 --> 00:19:51,816
These events are exactly
like one your plots.

317
00:19:51,899 --> 00:19:55,152
That's what I've been saying.
Agatha, that's gotta mean something.

318
00:19:55,236 --> 00:20:00,282
But what? I've no answers, none.

319
00:20:00,658 --> 00:20:05,538
I'm sorry, all of you.
I'm truly sorry, but I've failed.

320
00:20:05,621 --> 00:20:08,666
If anyone can help us,
then it's the Doctor, not me.

321
00:20:18,259 --> 00:20:19,802
Do you know what I think?

322
00:20:19,885 --> 00:20:23,931
Those books of yours, one day,
they could turn them into films.

323
00:20:24,014 --> 00:20:27,727
-They could be talking pictures.
-Talking pictures?

324
00:20:27,810 --> 00:20:32,398
-Pictures that talk. What do you mean?
-Oh, blimey, I've done it again.

325
00:20:33,232 --> 00:20:37,236
I appreciate you're trying to be kind,
but you are right.

326
00:20:37,319 --> 00:20:42,032
These murders are like my own creations.
It's as though someone's mocking me.

327
00:20:42,158 --> 00:20:44,535
And I've had enough scorn
for one lifetime.

328
00:20:44,660 --> 00:20:49,540
Yeah. The thing is,
I had this bloke once.

329
00:20:49,623 --> 00:20:54,128
I was engaged and I loved him.
I really did.

330
00:20:54,211 --> 00:20:56,714
Turns out,
he was lying through his teeth.

331
00:20:56,839 --> 00:20:59,175
But you know what? I moved on.

332
00:20:59,258 --> 00:21:03,721
I was lucky. I found the Doctor.
He's changed my life.

333
00:21:03,804 --> 00:21:07,266
-There's always someone else.
-1 see.

334
00:21:07,349 --> 00:21:11,937
-Is my marriage the stuff of gossip now?
-No, I just... I'm sorry.

335
00:21:13,981 --> 00:21:18,527
No matter, the stories are true.
I found my husband with another woman.

336
00:21:19,487 --> 00:21:22,156
A younger, prettier woman.
Isn't it always the way?

337
00:21:22,239 --> 00:21:27,578
Well, mine was with a giant spider,
but, same difference.

338
00:21:27,703 --> 00:21:30,581
You and the Doctor talk
such wonderful nonsense.

339
00:21:30,664 --> 00:21:33,918
Agatha, people love your books.
They really do.

340
00:21:34,001 --> 00:21:37,129
They're gonna be reading them
for years to come.

341
00:21:37,213 --> 00:21:40,716
If only. Try as I might,
it's hardly great literature.

342
00:21:40,800 --> 00:21:45,721
That's beyond me.
I'm afraid my books will be forgotten,

343
00:21:45,805 --> 00:21:47,723
like ephemera.

344
00:21:50,017 --> 00:21:51,811
Hello, what's that?

345
00:21:52,728 --> 00:21:55,022
Those flowerbeds
were perfectly neat earlier.

346
00:21:55,105 --> 00:21:57,691
Now some of the stalks are bent over.

347
00:22:02,696 --> 00:22:07,201
There you go. Who'd ever notice that?
You're brilliant.

348
00:22:09,078 --> 00:22:13,374
Oh! Someone came here tooled up.

349
00:22:13,457 --> 00:22:15,751
This is the sort of stuff
a thief would use.

350
00:22:15,835 --> 00:22:20,339
-The Unicorn, he's here.
-The Unicorn and the wasp.

351
00:22:20,422 --> 00:22:24,593
-Your drinks, ladies. Doctor.
-Very good, Greeves.

352
00:22:27,429 --> 00:22:29,473
How about the science stuff,
what did you find?

353
00:22:29,598 --> 00:22:33,060
Hmm. Vespiform sting.

354
00:22:33,143 --> 00:22:35,771
Vespiforms have got hives
in the Silfrax Galaxy.

355
00:22:35,855 --> 00:22:37,815
Again, you talk like Edward Lear.

356
00:22:37,940 --> 00:22:41,527
For some reason, this one's behaving
like a character in one of your books.

357
00:22:41,610 --> 00:22:43,988
DONNA: Come on, Agatha,
what would Miss Marple do?

358
00:22:44,071 --> 00:22:46,198
She'd have overheard
something vital by now,

359
00:22:46,282 --> 00:22:49,034
because the murderer thinks
she's just a harmless old lady.

360
00:22:49,118 --> 00:22:50,619
Clever idea.

361
00:22:51,662 --> 00:22:54,832
Miss Marple, who writes those?

362
00:22:54,957 --> 00:22:57,501
Copyright Donna Noble.
Add it to the list.

363
00:22:57,585 --> 00:22:59,587
-Donna.
-Okay, we could split the copyright.

364
00:22:59,670 --> 00:23:03,507
No. Something's inhibiting my enzymes.

365
00:23:03,591 --> 00:23:07,803
(GRUNTING) I've been poisoned.

366
00:23:07,928 --> 00:23:10,431
What do we do? What do we do?

367
00:23:10,514 --> 00:23:14,935
It runs. It's cyanide.
Sparkling cyanide.

368
00:23:17,980 --> 00:23:19,356
(GRUNTING)

369
00:23:21,984 --> 00:23:23,110
-Ginger beer!
-I beg you pardon?

370
00:23:23,235 --> 00:23:26,822
-I need ginger beer.
-The gentleman has gone mad!

371
00:23:27,323 --> 00:23:30,159
I'm an expert in poisons, Doctor.
There's no cure.

372
00:23:30,242 --> 00:23:31,702
It's fatal.

373
00:23:32,536 --> 00:23:35,247
Not for me. I can stimulate
the inhibited enzymes into reversal.

374
00:23:35,331 --> 00:23:37,583
Protein. I need protein.

375
00:23:37,666 --> 00:23:39,919
-Walnuts?
-Bring it.

376
00:23:42,588 --> 00:23:45,049
Can't understand you. How many words?

377
00:23:45,132 --> 00:23:49,929
One. One word. Shake! Milk! Shake!
Milk! Milk! No, not milk!

378
00:23:50,012 --> 00:23:51,889
Um, shake, shake, shake!

379
00:23:52,014 --> 00:23:53,849
Cocktail shake!
You want a Harvey Wallbanger!

380
00:23:53,933 --> 00:23:56,393
-Harvey Wallbanger?
-Well, I don't know!

381
00:23:56,477 --> 00:23:58,062
How is Harvey Wallbanger one word!

382
00:23:58,145 --> 00:24:00,564
-What do you need, Doctor?
-Salt!

383
00:24:00,648 --> 00:24:02,983
I was miming salt.
Salt, I need something salty!

384
00:24:03,067 --> 00:24:05,319
-What about this?
-What is it?

385
00:24:05,402 --> 00:24:06,695
-Salt!
-That's too salty.

386
00:24:06,779 --> 00:24:09,365
-Oh, that's too salty.
-What about this?

387
00:24:09,448 --> 00:24:10,783
-Mmm...
-What's that?

388
00:24:10,866 --> 00:24:13,953
-Anchovies.
-What is it? What else?

389
00:24:14,411 --> 00:24:17,665
Um, it's a song! "Mammy"?

390
00:24:17,790 --> 00:24:21,377
-I don't know! Camptown Races.
-Camptown Races?

391
00:24:21,460 --> 00:24:23,879
All right, then. Towering Inferno!

392
00:24:23,963 --> 00:24:26,048
It's a shock! Look, shock.
I need a shock!

393
00:24:26,173 --> 00:24:28,926
All right, then, big shock, coming up.

394
00:24:29,009 --> 00:24:30,386
(GAGGING)

395
00:24:38,644 --> 00:24:40,062
(GRUNTING)

396
00:24:43,899 --> 00:24:45,693
Detox! Oh!

397
00:24:46,860 --> 00:24:51,824
I must do that more often.
I mean the...the detox.

398
00:24:51,907 --> 00:24:55,661
Doctor, you are impossible. Who are you?

399
00:25:01,875 --> 00:25:06,171
Terrible day for all of us.
The professor struck down.

400
00:25:07,339 --> 00:25:12,469
Miss Chandrakala cruelly taken from us.
And yet we still take dinner.

401
00:25:12,594 --> 00:25:14,555
We are British, Doctor.

402
00:25:15,305 --> 00:25:17,266
What else must we do?

403
00:25:17,391 --> 00:25:20,019
DOCTOR: And then someone
tried to poison me.

404
00:25:20,811 --> 00:25:24,440
Any one of you had the chance
to put cyanide in my drink.

405
00:25:24,523 --> 00:25:27,735
-But it rather gave me an idea.
-And what would that be?

406
00:25:27,860 --> 00:25:29,820
Well, poison.

407
00:25:30,904 --> 00:25:31,989
Drink up.

408
00:25:32,114 --> 00:25:33,115
(CHOKES)

409
00:25:35,117 --> 00:25:40,456
-I've laced the soup with pepper.
-Mmm. I thought it was jolly spicy.

410
00:25:40,539 --> 00:25:43,792
But the active ingredient of pepper
is piperine.

411
00:25:44,460 --> 00:25:47,463
Traditionally used as an insecticide.

412
00:25:50,466 --> 00:25:52,718
Oh! Anyone got the shivers?

413
00:25:55,262 --> 00:25:56,555
(GASPS)

414
00:25:57,848 --> 00:26:00,100
-What the deuce...
-Listen, listen, listen.

415
00:26:00,184 --> 00:26:02,186
(WASP BUZZING)

416
00:26:02,311 --> 00:26:03,771
No, it can't be.

417
00:26:05,064 --> 00:26:06,482
(GASPING)

418
00:26:09,151 --> 00:26:11,987
-Show yourself, demon.
-DOCTOR: Nobody move.

419
00:26:14,198 --> 00:26:16,408
Oh, no. Stay where you are!

420
00:26:24,666 --> 00:26:26,710
Out, out, out, out, now!

421
00:26:29,797 --> 00:26:32,633
I'll cover you, Agatha. You've got
a long, long life to lead yet.

422
00:26:32,716 --> 00:26:34,426
Well, we know the butler didn't do it.

423
00:26:34,510 --> 00:26:35,969
Then, who did?

424
00:26:44,770 --> 00:26:50,734
My jewellery! The Firestone!
It's gone! Stolen!

425
00:26:51,276 --> 00:26:52,528
Roger.

426
00:26:52,694 --> 00:26:54,071
(SCREAMING)

427
00:26:56,240 --> 00:26:59,535
My son... My child!

428
00:27:22,141 --> 00:27:23,934
That poor footman!

429
00:27:25,435 --> 00:27:28,230
Roger is dead
and he can't even mourn him.

430
00:27:28,313 --> 00:27:31,358
1926, it's more like the Dark Ages.

431
00:27:31,692 --> 00:27:33,944
Did you inquire after the necklace?

432
00:27:34,027 --> 00:27:37,239
Lady Eddison brought it back from India.
It's worth thousands.

433
00:27:37,322 --> 00:27:39,950
DOCTOR: This thing can sting,
it can fly.

434
00:27:41,743 --> 00:27:45,330
It could wipe us all out in seconds.
Why is playing this game?

435
00:27:45,414 --> 00:27:48,000
Every murder is essentially the same.

436
00:27:48,083 --> 00:27:50,961
They're committed
because somebody wants something.

437
00:27:51,044 --> 00:27:53,714
-What does a Vespiform want?
-Doctor, stop it.

438
00:27:53,797 --> 00:27:56,550
The murderer is as human as you or I.

439
00:27:57,968 --> 00:27:59,511
You're right.

440
00:27:59,595 --> 00:28:02,264
Oh, I've been so caught up
with giant wasps,

441
00:28:02,347 --> 00:28:04,474
I'd forgotten you're the expert.

442
00:28:04,600 --> 00:28:08,645
I'm not, I've told you.
I'm just a purveyor of nonsense.

443
00:28:08,770 --> 00:28:10,272
Oh, no, no, no, no.

444
00:28:10,355 --> 00:28:12,983
'Cause plenty of people write detective
stories, but yours are the best.

445
00:28:13,066 --> 00:28:16,445
Why? Why are you so good,
Agatha Christie?

446
00:28:16,945 --> 00:28:20,282
Because you understand. You've lived.

447
00:28:21,491 --> 00:28:23,994
You've fought,
you've had your heart broken.

448
00:28:24,953 --> 00:28:26,914
You know about people.

449
00:28:26,997 --> 00:28:31,752
Their passions, their hope and despair
and anger, all of those tiny,

450
00:28:31,835 --> 00:28:36,506
huge things that can turn
the most ordinary person into a killer.

451
00:28:37,382 --> 00:28:42,888
Just think, Agatha.
If anyone can solve this, it's you.

452
00:28:46,016 --> 00:28:49,186
I've called you here,
on this endless night,

453
00:28:50,229 --> 00:28:52,898
because we have a murderer in our midst.

454
00:28:52,981 --> 00:28:56,151
And when it comes to detection,
there's none finer.

455
00:28:56,235 --> 00:28:59,988
Ladies and gentlemen,
I give you Agatha Christie.

456
00:29:03,575 --> 00:29:07,871
This is a crooked house.
A house of secrets.

457
00:29:08,914 --> 00:29:12,417
To understand the solution,
we must examine them all.

458
00:29:13,126 --> 00:29:16,380
Starting with you, Miss Redmond.

459
00:29:19,925 --> 00:29:24,096
-But I'm innocent, surely.
-You've never met these people.

460
00:29:24,179 --> 00:29:26,848
And these people have never met you.

461
00:29:27,557 --> 00:29:31,561
I think the real Robina Redmond never
left London. You're impersonating her.

462
00:29:31,687 --> 00:29:35,315
How silly. What proof do you have?

463
00:29:35,399 --> 00:29:38,151
You said you'd been to the toilet...

464
00:29:38,527 --> 00:29:41,655
Oh, I know this. If she was really posh
she'd say loo.

465
00:29:41,738 --> 00:29:46,326
Earlier today,
Miss Noble and I found this on the lawn,

466
00:29:46,410 --> 00:29:49,246
right beneath your bathroom window.

467
00:29:49,371 --> 00:29:52,332
You must've heard that Miss Noble was
searching the bedroom, so you panicked.

468
00:29:52,416 --> 00:29:54,376
You ran upstairs
and disposed of the evidence.

469
00:29:58,714 --> 00:30:01,717
I've never seen that thing
before in my life.

470
00:30:01,842 --> 00:30:06,471
-What's inside it?
-The tools of your trade, Miss Redmond.

471
00:30:06,972 --> 00:30:10,892
Or should I say...the Unicorn?

472
00:30:10,976 --> 00:30:12,686
(GASPING)

473
00:30:12,769 --> 00:30:15,814
You came to this house
with one sole intention,

474
00:30:15,897 --> 00:30:18,525
to steal the Firestone.

475
00:30:19,109 --> 00:30:23,155
Oh, all right, then. It's a fair cop...

476
00:30:23,989 --> 00:30:29,244
Yes, I'm the bleeding Unicorn.
Ever so nice to meet you, I don't think.

477
00:30:29,369 --> 00:30:32,581
I took my chance in the dark
and nabbed it.

478
00:30:32,706 --> 00:30:35,042
Go on, then, you nobs.

479
00:30:35,125 --> 00:30:38,253
Arrest me. Sling me in jail.

480
00:30:39,963 --> 00:30:43,300
-So, is she the murderer?
-Don't be so thick.

481
00:30:43,425 --> 00:30:46,261
I might be a thief,
but I ain't no killer.

482
00:30:46,386 --> 00:30:52,601
Quite. There are darker motives at work
and in examining this household,

483
00:30:52,684 --> 00:30:54,770
we come to you,

484
00:30:54,853 --> 00:30:55,896
Colonel.

485
00:31:00,275 --> 00:31:04,154
Damn it, woman.
You with your perspicacity.

486
00:31:04,237 --> 00:31:06,073
You've rumbled me.

487
00:31:07,783 --> 00:31:09,659
(GASPS) You can walk!

488
00:31:10,535 --> 00:31:11,745
But why?

489
00:31:11,828 --> 00:31:16,625
My darling, how else could I be certain
of keeping you by my side?

490
00:31:16,750 --> 00:31:17,834
I don't understand.

491
00:31:17,918 --> 00:31:20,253
You're still a beautiful woman,
Clemency.

492
00:31:20,337 --> 00:31:23,382
Sooner or later,
some chap will turn your head.

493
00:31:23,465 --> 00:31:25,342
I couldn't bear that.

494
00:31:25,425 --> 00:31:29,971
Staying in the chair was the only way
I could be certain of keeping you.

495
00:31:30,847 --> 00:31:34,476
Confounded Mrs Christie!
How did you discover the truth?

496
00:31:34,601 --> 00:31:36,520
Um, actually I had no idea.

497
00:31:36,603 --> 00:31:38,647
I was just going to say
you were completely innocent.

498
00:31:38,772 --> 00:31:41,316
-Oh!
-Sorry.

499
00:31:42,150 --> 00:31:45,695
-Uh, shall I sit down, then?
-I think you better had.

500
00:31:47,239 --> 00:31:50,158
-So, he's not the murderer?
-Indeed not.

501
00:31:51,576 --> 00:31:54,329
To find the truth, let's return

502
00:31:55,747 --> 00:31:56,998
to this.

503
00:31:57,916 --> 00:32:01,670
Far more than the Unicorn's
object of desire.

504
00:32:02,879 --> 00:32:05,465
The Firestone has quite a history.

505
00:32:07,634 --> 00:32:10,095
-Lady Eddison...
-I've done nothing.

506
00:32:10,178 --> 00:32:12,222
You brought it back from India,
did you not?

507
00:32:12,347 --> 00:32:14,516
Before you met the Colonel.

508
00:32:14,933 --> 00:32:17,519
You came home with malaria

509
00:32:17,644 --> 00:32:21,022
and confined yourself to this house
for six months

510
00:32:21,148 --> 00:32:23,275
in a room that has been
kept locked ever since.

511
00:32:23,358 --> 00:32:25,986
-Which I rather think means...
-Stop, please.

512
00:32:26,069 --> 00:32:29,614
I'm so sorry,
but you had fallen pregnant in India.

513
00:32:30,282 --> 00:32:34,161
Unmarried and ashamed, you hurried back
to England with your confidante,

514
00:32:34,244 --> 00:32:37,456
a young maid, later to become
housekeeper, Miss Chandrakala.

515
00:32:37,539 --> 00:32:39,541
Clemency, is this true?

516
00:32:40,375 --> 00:32:45,589
My poor baby. I had to give him away.
The shame of it.

517
00:32:45,714 --> 00:32:47,257
HUGH: But you've never said a word.

518
00:32:47,382 --> 00:32:50,469
EDDISON: I had no choice.
Imagine the scandal.

519
00:32:50,552 --> 00:32:54,139
The family name.
I'm British, I carry on.

520
00:32:54,931 --> 00:32:57,434
And it was no ordinary pregnancy.

521
00:32:58,768 --> 00:33:00,145
How can you know that?

522
00:33:00,228 --> 00:33:01,855
Excuse me, Agatha, this is my territory.

523
00:33:01,938 --> 00:33:04,065
But when you heard that
buzzing sound in the dining room,

524
00:33:04,149 --> 00:33:06,067
you said, "It can't be".

525
00:33:07,194 --> 00:33:10,322
-Why did you say that?
-You'd never believe it.

526
00:33:10,405 --> 00:33:14,743
The Doctor has opened my mind
to believe many things.

527
00:33:16,077 --> 00:33:19,915
It was 40 years ago,
in the heat of Delhi late one night.

528
00:33:23,084 --> 00:33:28,590
I was alone and that's when I saw it:
a dazzling light in the sky.

529
00:33:29,424 --> 00:33:31,426
The next day he came to the house.

530
00:33:32,302 --> 00:33:35,639
Christopher, the most handsome man
I'd ever seen.

531
00:33:36,431 --> 00:33:39,809
Our love blazed like a wildfire.

532
00:33:41,269 --> 00:33:43,188
I held nothing back.

533
00:33:46,441 --> 00:33:48,193
And in return,

534
00:33:48,276 --> 00:33:51,613
he showed me an incredible truth
about himself.

535
00:33:52,614 --> 00:33:56,034
He'd made himself human
to learn about us.

536
00:33:56,159 --> 00:33:59,037
This was his true shape.

537
00:34:00,288 --> 00:34:05,210
I loved him so much, it didn't matter.
But he was stolen from me.

538
00:34:05,293 --> 00:34:08,255
1885, the year of the great monsoon,

539
00:34:09,422 --> 00:34:12,592
the river Jamuna rose up
and broke its banks.

540
00:34:12,676 --> 00:34:14,970
He was taken with the flood.

541
00:34:16,763 --> 00:34:21,560
But Christopher left me a parting gift,
a jewel like no other.

542
00:34:21,643 --> 00:34:24,521
I wore it always,
part of me never forgot.

543
00:34:24,813 --> 00:34:26,648
I kept it close...

544
00:34:28,149 --> 00:34:29,359
Always.

545
00:34:29,442 --> 00:34:31,069
Just like a man.

546
00:34:31,194 --> 00:34:34,114
Flashes his family jewels
and you end up with a bun in the oven.

547
00:34:34,197 --> 00:34:36,032
AGATHA: A poor little child.

548
00:34:36,992 --> 00:34:40,412
Forty years ago, Miss Chandrakala took
that newborn baby to an orphanage.

549
00:34:40,495 --> 00:34:44,332
But Professor Peach worked it out.
He found the birth certificate.

550
00:34:44,416 --> 00:34:47,252
-Oh, that's maiden. Maiden name.
-AGATHA: Precisely.

551
00:34:47,335 --> 00:34:49,629
-So, she killed him.
-I did not!

552
00:34:49,713 --> 00:34:53,508
Miss Chandrakala feared that
the Professor had unearthed your secret.

553
00:34:53,633 --> 00:34:54,926
She was coming to warn you.

554
00:34:55,010 --> 00:34:56,928
-So, she killed her.
-I did not!

555
00:34:57,012 --> 00:35:00,181
Lady Eddison is innocent.

556
00:35:01,433 --> 00:35:03,268
Because at this point...

557
00:35:03,351 --> 00:35:04,519
Doctor.

558
00:35:05,061 --> 00:35:09,691
Thank you! At this point, when
we consider the lies and the secrets

559
00:35:09,774 --> 00:35:11,651
that are key to these events,

560
00:35:11,735 --> 00:35:15,905
then we have to consider
it was you, Donna Noble.

561
00:35:17,324 --> 00:35:19,409
What? What did I kill?

562
00:35:19,492 --> 00:35:22,871
No, but you said it all along,
the vital clue,

563
00:35:22,954 --> 00:35:25,498
that this whole thing is being acted out
like a murder mystery.

564
00:35:25,582 --> 00:35:30,170
Which means, it was you,
Agatha Christie.

565
00:35:31,046 --> 00:35:33,256
I beg your pardon, sir?

566
00:35:33,340 --> 00:35:35,800
-So, she killed them?
-No, but she wrote.

567
00:35:35,884 --> 00:35:40,263
She wrote those brilliant, clever books
and who is her greatest admirer?

568
00:35:40,388 --> 00:35:43,725
The moving finger points at you...

569
00:35:44,309 --> 00:35:47,145
-Lady Eddison.
-Oh, leave me alone.

570
00:35:47,228 --> 00:35:49,272
-So, she did kill them.
-No.

571
00:35:49,397 --> 00:35:52,984
But just think. Last Thursday night,
what were you doing?

572
00:35:53,068 --> 00:35:56,988
Uh, I was, uh, I was in the library.

573
00:35:59,407 --> 00:36:01,451
I was reading my favourite
Agatha Christie,

574
00:36:01,576 --> 00:36:05,080
thinking about her plots
and how clever she must be.

575
00:36:05,413 --> 00:36:08,083
-How is that relevant?
-Just think.

576
00:36:08,708 --> 00:36:11,419
What else happened on Thursday night?

577
00:36:15,090 --> 00:36:18,343
-I'm sorry?
-You said on the lawn this afternoon.

578
00:36:18,426 --> 00:36:21,513
Last Thursday night,
those boys broke into your church.

579
00:36:21,596 --> 00:36:24,099
That's correct. They did.

580
00:36:28,937 --> 00:36:32,023
I discovered the two of them.
Thieves in the night.

581
00:36:32,107 --> 00:36:34,025
I was most perturbed.

582
00:36:34,567 --> 00:36:38,321
What the blazes are you doing, boys?

583
00:36:38,405 --> 00:36:39,698
(LAUGHING)

584
00:36:40,615 --> 00:36:42,742
But I apprehended them.

585
00:36:43,326 --> 00:36:46,621
Really? A man of God
against two strong lads?

586
00:36:46,705 --> 00:36:52,043
A man in his 40's?
Or should I say, 40 years old?

587
00:36:52,877 --> 00:36:55,463
-Exactly.
-Oh, my God!

588
00:36:57,424 --> 00:37:01,803
Lady Eddison, your child,
how old would he be now?

589
00:37:01,928 --> 00:37:04,723
Forty! He's 40.

590
00:37:05,432 --> 00:37:07,517
Your child has come home.

591
00:37:07,976 --> 00:37:11,271
-This is poppycock.
-DOCTOR: Oh?

592
00:37:11,354 --> 00:37:13,273
You said you were taught
by the Christian fathers,

593
00:37:13,398 --> 00:37:16,109
meaning, raised in an orphanage.

594
00:37:16,192 --> 00:37:19,237
My son! Can it be?

595
00:37:19,320 --> 00:37:22,866
You found those thieves, Reverend,
and you got angry.

596
00:37:22,991 --> 00:37:25,243
A proper, deep anger for the first time
in your life

597
00:37:25,326 --> 00:37:27,704
and it broke the genetic lock.

598
00:37:27,996 --> 00:37:28,955
You changed.

599
00:37:32,167 --> 00:37:38,757
(BUZZING) Put those things back
where you found them.

600
00:37:38,840 --> 00:37:40,258
It's...

601
00:37:50,059 --> 00:37:53,938
You realised your inheritance
after all these years.

602
00:37:55,190 --> 00:37:56,941
You knew who you were.

603
00:37:57,025 --> 00:38:00,028
Oh! And then it all kicks off.
'Cause this isn't just a jewel.

604
00:38:00,153 --> 00:38:05,366
It's a Vespiform telepathic recorder.
It's part of you, your brain.

605
00:38:05,909 --> 00:38:07,285
Your very essence.

606
00:38:07,368 --> 00:38:10,455
And when you activated,
so did the Firestone.

607
00:38:10,538 --> 00:38:13,792
It beamed your full identity
directly into your mind.

608
00:38:13,875 --> 00:38:15,502
And at the same time,

609
00:38:16,336 --> 00:38:20,840
it absorbed the works of Agatha Christie
directly from Lady Eddison.

610
00:38:20,965 --> 00:38:23,051
It all became part of you.

611
00:38:23,426 --> 00:38:27,222
The mechanics of those novels
re-templated in your brain.

612
00:38:27,889 --> 00:38:29,557
You killed in this pattern,

613
00:38:29,641 --> 00:38:32,185
because that's what you think
the world is.

614
00:38:32,268 --> 00:38:34,813
Turns out we are in the middle
of a murder mystery.

615
00:38:34,896 --> 00:38:38,066
-One of yours, Dame Agatha.
-Dame?

616
00:38:38,149 --> 00:38:40,276
Oh! It's all right, not yet.

617
00:38:40,360 --> 00:38:45,156
-So he killed them? Yes? Definitely?
-Yes.

618
00:38:45,782 --> 00:38:47,075
Well...

619
00:38:47,909 --> 00:38:51,412
This has certainly been
a most entertaining evening.

620
00:38:52,247 --> 00:38:55,542
Really, you can't believe any of this,
surely, Lady Eddison?

621
00:38:55,625 --> 00:38:56,668
(BUZZES)

622
00:38:56,918 --> 00:38:58,253
Lady who?

623
00:38:59,003 --> 00:39:01,256
(BUZZING) Lady Eddison...

624
00:39:01,339 --> 00:39:05,009
-Little bit of buzzing there, Vicar.
-Don't make me angry!

625
00:39:05,093 --> 00:39:07,178
Why? What happens then?

626
00:39:08,012 --> 00:39:11,516
(BUZZING) Damn it! You humans

627
00:39:11,599 --> 00:39:14,269
worshipping your tribal sky gods...

628
00:39:14,936 --> 00:39:16,813
I am so much more.

629
00:39:16,938 --> 00:39:20,108
That night, the universe
exploded in my mind.

630
00:39:20,191 --> 00:39:23,194
(BUZZING) I wanted to take
what was mine!

631
00:39:23,278 --> 00:39:29,033
And you, Agatha Christie, with your
railway station bookstall romances...

632
00:39:30,076 --> 00:39:32,495
What's to stop me killing you?

633
00:39:32,620 --> 00:39:35,206
Oh, my dear God. My child!

634
00:39:35,290 --> 00:39:38,543
What's to stop me killing you all?

635
00:39:38,626 --> 00:39:39,961
(BUZZING)

636
00:39:41,796 --> 00:39:44,048
-It's me...
-No, no. Clemency, come back...

637
00:39:44,132 --> 00:39:46,551
Keep away. Keep away, my God!

638
00:39:46,634 --> 00:39:49,721
No! No! No more murder.

639
00:39:49,804 --> 00:39:51,556
If my imagination made you Kkill,

640
00:39:51,639 --> 00:39:55,768
then my imagination will find a way
to stop you, foul creature.

641
00:39:57,145 --> 00:39:58,563
(SCREAMING)

642
00:39:59,939 --> 00:40:02,150
Run! He's chasing us.

643
00:40:06,446 --> 00:40:07,947
(HONKING)

644
00:40:09,824 --> 00:40:12,285
AGATHA: Come here!
Come and get me, Reverend!

645
00:40:12,368 --> 00:40:14,329
Agatha, what are you doing?

646
00:40:14,454 --> 00:40:16,998
If I started this, Doctor,
then I must stop it.

647
00:40:20,084 --> 00:40:21,377
Come on!

648
00:40:33,514 --> 00:40:36,768
It's all my fault. It's all my fault.
It's all my fault.

649
00:40:39,479 --> 00:40:42,106
You said this is the night
Agatha Christie loses her memory?

650
00:40:42,190 --> 00:40:43,816
Time is in flux, Donna.

651
00:40:43,900 --> 00:40:46,319
For all we know, this is the night
Agatha Christie loses her life

652
00:40:46,402 --> 00:40:47,779
and history gets changed.

653
00:40:47,862 --> 00:40:49,614
But where is she going?

654
00:40:50,615 --> 00:40:52,033
(WASP SCREECHING)

655
00:41:02,043 --> 00:41:05,713
The lake! She's heading for the lake.
What's she doing?

656
00:41:13,638 --> 00:41:16,641
Here I am, the honey in the trap.

657
00:41:17,308 --> 00:41:19,978
-Come to me, Vespiform.
-She's controlling him!

658
00:41:20,061 --> 00:41:22,855
His mind is based on her
thought processes. They're linked!

659
00:41:22,939 --> 00:41:27,402
Quite so, Doctor. If I die,
then this creature might die with me.

660
00:41:28,403 --> 00:41:29,821
Don't hurt her!

661
00:41:29,904 --> 00:41:33,324
You're not meant to be like this.
You've got the wrong template your mind.

662
00:41:33,408 --> 00:41:35,201
DONNA: He's not listening.

663
00:42:00,435 --> 00:42:02,395
How do you kill a wasp?

664
00:42:03,104 --> 00:42:06,149
Drown him, just like his father.

665
00:42:06,274 --> 00:42:09,610
-Donna, that thing couldn't help itself.
-Neither could I.

666
00:42:14,949 --> 00:42:18,911
Death comes as the end
and justice is served.

667
00:42:20,288 --> 00:42:22,623
Murder at the Vicar's Rage.

668
00:42:24,208 --> 00:42:28,379
-Needs a bit of work.
-Just one mystery left, Doctor.

669
00:42:29,547 --> 00:42:31,758
Who exactly are you?

670
00:42:32,383 --> 00:42:33,801
(GROANING)

671
00:42:34,969 --> 00:42:38,514
Oh, it's the Firestone.
It's part of the Vespiform's mind.

672
00:42:38,639 --> 00:42:41,517
It's dying and it's connected to Agatha.

673
00:42:49,150 --> 00:42:50,568
(EXHALES)

674
00:42:50,651 --> 00:42:52,236
He let her go.

675
00:42:52,987 --> 00:42:56,657
Right at the end, the Vespiform chose
to save someone's life.

676
00:42:56,741 --> 00:43:00,203
-Is she all right, though?
-Oh, of course, the amnesia.

677
00:43:00,286 --> 00:43:02,997
Wiped her mind of everything
that happened, the wasp, the murders...

678
00:43:03,122 --> 00:43:06,417
And us. She'll forget about us.

679
00:43:06,501 --> 00:43:11,255
Yeah, but we solved another riddle.
The mystery of Agatha Christie.

680
00:43:11,339 --> 00:43:15,635
And tomorrow morning, her car
gets found by the side of the lake.

681
00:43:16,177 --> 00:43:20,056
A few days later,
she turns up in a hotel in Harrogate.

682
00:43:20,181 --> 00:43:22,725
With no idea of what just happened.

683
00:43:28,106 --> 00:43:29,982
No one will ever know.

684
00:43:31,484 --> 00:43:35,071
DONNA: Lady Eddison, the Colonel,
and all the staff, what about them?

685
00:43:35,154 --> 00:43:38,574
Shameful story.
They'll never talk of it. Too British.

686
00:43:39,075 --> 00:43:43,371
While the Unicorn does a bunk
back to London town,

687
00:43:43,454 --> 00:43:45,414
she can even say she was never there.

688
00:43:46,374 --> 00:43:49,460
-What happens to Agatha?
-Oh, great life!

689
00:43:49,544 --> 00:43:51,796
Met another man. Married again.

690
00:43:51,879 --> 00:43:54,799
Toured the world.
Wrote and wrote and wrote.

691
00:43:54,882 --> 00:43:57,385
She never thought her books
were any good, though.

692
00:43:57,468 --> 00:44:00,763
And she must have spent
all those years wondering.

693
00:44:02,723 --> 00:44:06,435
Thing is...
I don't think she ever quite forgot.

694
00:44:08,020 --> 00:44:11,816
Great mind like that, some of
the details kept bleeding through.

695
00:44:11,899 --> 00:44:15,403
All the stuff her imagination could use,
like, Miss Marple.

696
00:44:15,528 --> 00:44:19,657
-I should have made her sign a contract.
-And where is it? Where is it? Hold on.

697
00:44:21,534 --> 00:44:22,994
Here we go.

698
00:44:26,289 --> 00:44:27,540
C!

699
00:44:29,876 --> 00:44:32,211
That is C for Cybermen,

700
00:44:33,296 --> 00:44:35,256
C for Carrionites...

701
00:44:37,633 --> 00:44:41,470
And... Christie, Agatha!

702
00:44:42,180 --> 00:44:44,891
-Look at that.
-She did remember.

703
00:44:44,974 --> 00:44:48,269
Somewhere at the back of her mind,
it all lingered.

704
00:44:49,604 --> 00:44:52,773
And that's not all.
Look at the copyright page.

705
00:44:57,069 --> 00:45:00,281
"Facsimile Edition,
published in the year..."

706
00:45:03,576 --> 00:45:07,663
-Five billion?
-People never stop reading them.

707
00:45:07,788 --> 00:45:10,958
She is the bestselling novelist
of all time.

708
00:45:11,792 --> 00:45:14,712
(SIGHS) But she never knew.

709
00:45:14,795 --> 00:45:16,380
Well, no one knows
how they're going to be remembered,

710
00:45:16,464 --> 00:45:20,801
all you can do is hope for the best.
Maybe that's what kept her writing.

711
00:45:21,552 --> 00:45:23,971
Same thing keeps me travelling.

712
00:45:24,847 --> 00:45:26,265
Onwards?

713
00:45:27,350 --> 00:45:28,684
Onwards.

714
00:45:33,773 --> 00:45:37,443
This is the biggest library
in the universe. So where is everyone?

715
00:45:39,278 --> 00:45:41,656
Run. For God's sake, run.

716
00:45:41,781 --> 00:45:42,907
Run!

717
00:45:47,954 --> 00:45:50,706
Professor River Song, Archaeologist.

718
00:45:50,831 --> 00:45:52,500
The shadows are moving again.

719
00:45:52,583 --> 00:45:53,960
MAN: How can a shadow be infected?

720
00:45:54,043 --> 00:45:55,378
It's a Vashta Nerada.

721
00:45:55,503 --> 00:45:57,296
-WOMAN: Run!
-What's CAL?

722
00:45:57,380 --> 00:46:00,132
So, they came to this library
and killed everything in it?

723
00:46:00,258 --> 00:46:02,051
-Donna?
-Yeah.

724
00:46:02,385 --> 00:46:03,552
Stay out of the shadows.

725
00:46:03,678 --> 00:46:04,679
(WOMAN SCREAMING)

